metencephalon","Prosencephalon, mesencephalon, rhombencephalon","Diencephalon, mesencephalon, myelencephalon","Telencephalon, diencephalon, rhombencephalon"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe three primary brain vesicles develop in a specific anterior-to-posterior sequence: \u003Cstrong\u003Eprosencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (forebrain), \u003Cstrong\u003Emesencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (midbrain), and \u003Cstrong\u003Erhombencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (hindbrain).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary vesicles then undergo further subdivision:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe prosencephalon divides into the \u003Cstrong\u003Etelencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (forms cerebral hemispheres) and \u003Cstrong\u003Ediencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (forms thalamus, hypothalamus, and retina)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe mesencephalon remains undivided\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe rhombencephalon divides into the \u003Cstrong\u003Emetencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (forms pons and cerebellum) and \u003Cstrong\u003Emyelencephalon\u003C/strong\u003E (forms medulla oblongata)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options mix primary and secondary vesicles or list them in incorrect anatomical order.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary brain vesicles form in week four of development: prosencephalon (forebrain), mesencephalon (midbrain), and rhombencephalon (hindbrain).","The prosencephalon develops into the telencephalon and diencephalon.","The rhombencephalon develops into the metencephalon and myelencephalon."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRev